President Obama weighs in on the controversy over whether peas should go in guacamole
President Obama decided to share his thoughts on what makes a proper guacamole on Twitter today. According to him, peas should not be included: respect the nyt, but not buying peas in guac. onions, garlic, hot peppers. classic.  
 
 The president was taking questions about health care and the Affordable Care Act in a Twitter Q&A session: Hello from Nashville! I'll be answering your questions on health care and the Affordable Care Act at 3:30pm ET. Tweet yours using  . 
 
 So naturally, Justin Green, the political editor of IJReview, asked the president about the afternoon's most pressing Twitter controversy — whether peas should be included in guacamole:  Do you agree with the   about putting peas in guacamole? If yes, why? 
 
 Earlier in the afternoon, the   sent the following Tweet, with a link to a recipe: Add green peas to your guacamole. Trust us.    
 
 The absurd suggestion — and the  ' assurance that we should "trust" it — had already led to many expressions of outrage, particularly on politics and journalism Twitter, before President Obama weighed in: The   declared war on Texas when they suggested adding green peas to guacamole.    
 
